      <hedline>
        <hl1>Central Park Terror: The Outcry</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Katharine J Hamerton letter on mob assault in Central Park and reports of police indifference to violence; says culture of Police Department must be addressed in terms of its tolerance of sexual violence, and we should also take occasion to revisit discussion of this country's attitude toward women</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Inquiry Focuses on Officers' Responses to Violence in Park After Parade'' (news article, June 14), about the mob assault in Central Park on Sunday and reports of police indifference to the violence:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Inquiry Focuses on Officers' Responses to Violence in Park After Parade'' (news article, June 14), about the mob assault in Central Park on Sunday and reports of police indifference to the violence:</p>
        <p>How can any woman feel safe in public in New York City if this is true? Such chilling indifference shows a culture of tolerance toward sexual aggression against women in public places. What would we be saying if the same attacks had occurred on blacks or members of another minority group?</p>
        <p>This incident shows that as a society, we allow women to venture into public only on suffrage. The culture of the Police Department must be addressed in terms of its tolerance of sexual violence, and we should also take this occasion to revisit a discussion of this country's attitudes toward women.</p>
        <p>KATHARINE J. HAMERTON  Chicago, June 14, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
